It is quite common to have the same versions on multiple projects, that will have the same release dates (specially when using an Agile board with multiple projects).

When those versions are released, they will probably have the same release name and notes. Currently, this is done manually, one release notes per version in each project. It would be useful to have one release notes that could be applied to all versions in different projects.

h3. Summary
When the user is marked as inactive, the current user session is not killed

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a test user;
# Login with the test user on a different browser or using incognito/private mode;
# Go to the user administration and mark the user as inactive;

h3. Expected Results
The test user session to be killed;

h3. Actual Results
The test user loses acess to the applications but remains logged in in JIRA as the session is not killed once the user is marked as inactive.

I want to be able to change Issue numbering scheme: 
 from 

{noformat}
<project key>-<issue number>
{noformat}

 to 

{noformat}
<project key>/<year>-<issue number> or <project key>/<year>/<month>-<issue number>
{noformat}

 e.g. TST/2018-382 or AD/2018/07-12236

So that in each period (Year or Month) the numbering starts from 1 e.g. AD/2018/01-1, AD/2018/01-2 ... AD/2018/01-572, AD/2018/02-1, AD/2018/02-2 ... e.t.c
 With the possibility of different settings in different Jira projects.

In the Conneting Jira to SQL 2014 documentation for Jira 7.10 and 7.11 there exists a problem with the sample dbconfig.xml currently.

 

Docs:

[https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver0710/connecting-jira-applications-to-sql-server-2014-953144226.html]

[https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver/connecting-jira-applications-to-sql-server-2014-938846861.html]

 

The sample dbconfig.xml has the example:

 {quote}
 <url>jdbc:sqlserver://;serverName=dbserver;portNumber=1433;databaseName=jiradb</url> 
{quote}

However I'm confident that there should not be a ';' before the first parameter.  But it also curious that these guides indicate to use a serverName= at all.  In all the other documents for Connecting to 2012, 2016, and previous 2014 versions, the example URL tag looks like this


{quote}
<url>jdbc:sqlserver://dbserver:1433;databaseName=jiradb</url> 
{quote}
 
Please check this once more.  It's ok if there are alternative ways to configure this. But at the very least we need to be sure that our examples work, and I'm confident that if a user tried to use this as we have shown, it would cause Jira to fail to start up.
